Text: The experiment you will perform is a variation on a task known as the "beads task".
In this variant of the experiment, there are 9 jars containing various proportions of red and green beads.
One jar is chosen at random and covered, hiding the beads.
8 beads are randomly drawn from this jar.
A new bead will then be drawn from the jar.
Your task is to guess what colour (red or green) this next bead will be.
You will perform this experiment with four other (simulated) participants.
You will be able to see their guess (but not their beads), as well as see how confident they are in their guess.
Unlike the original "beads task", you therefore have access to additional social information.
We will perform 5 practice trials without the other participants to help you understand how the task works.
You will now perform the same experiment, but you will do so alongside four other (simulated) agents.
As before, each agent will draw 8 random beads, guess the colour of the next bead and state their confidence, then replace all the beads back into the jar.
All the agents, along with yourself, will be drawing beads from the same jar.
Though do note that you will all replace the beads back into the jar before the next participant/agent has their turn.
Their choice of colour and confidence will be shown using the above four images.
You can therefore use the agents decisions to inform your own decision about the colour of the next bead.
You will not need to state your confidence in this part of the experiment. You only need to guess the colour of the next bead.
